Unpleasant Index: Which airline should be avoided?

unpleasant <- 0 
airlines <- unique(flights_cleaned$AIRLINE)

# for a long/short haul flight, what is the maximum delay before it is considered unpleasant
# assume that it is unpleasant if a flight gets cancelled or diverted
# arrival refers to the maximum duration of delay before it is considered unpleasant (after accounting for departure delay)
# "a" represents the selected airline
unpleasant.index <- function(long,short,arrival,a)
{
  flights.a <- flights_cleaned %>% filter(AIRLINE==airlines[a])  
  unpleasant <- sum(flights.a$CANCELLED, flights.a$DIVERTED)
  
  for (j in range(1:nrow(flights.a)))
  {
  if (!is.na(flights.a$AIRLINE_DELAY[j]) | !is.na(flights.a$LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY[j]))
  {
  #long haul are  more than 6 hours, short haul are less 6 hours
  #considered unpleasant for delay of 60 mins for long haul
  #considered unpleasant for delay of more than 15 mins for short haul
    if (flights.a$SCHEDULED_TIME[j]>300 & flights.a$DEPARTURE_DELAY[j]>long)
    {
  unpleasant <- unpleasant + 1
    }
    if (flights.a$SCHEDULED_TIME[j]<300 & flights.a$DEPARTURE_DELAY[j]<short &  flights.a$DEPARTURE_DELAY[j] >0)
    {
      unpleasant <- unpleasant + 1
    }
    
    if((flights.a$ARRIVAL_DELAY[j]-flights.a$DEPARTURE_DELAY[j])>arrival)
    {
      unpleasant <- unpleasant + 1
    }
  }
  }
  return(unpleasant/nrow(flights.a))
}


avoid <- data.frame(matrix(nrow=length(airlines),ncol=2))
names(avoid) <- c("Airline","Unpleasant_Index")                  
avoid$Airline <- airlines
avoid$Unpleasant_Index <- 1:14
avoid$Unpleasant_Index <- sapply(avoid$Unpleasant_Index,unpleasant.index,long=45,short=15,arrival=15)

ggplot(avoid, aes(x=reorder(Airline,Unpleasant_Index),y=Unpleasant_Index, fill=Airline)) + geom_bar(stat="identity",width=0.7) +
  labs(title="Unpleasant Index across Airlines",y="Unpleasant Index") +
  theme(axis.title.x=element_blank(),legend.position = "none")

From the bar graph above, we can actually infer that airline MQ has the highest unpleasant index followed by EV and US. We would consider the unpleasant index as a more holistic measure as compared to percentage of flights delayed. This is because the index allows users to set their own threshold of what is unpleasant taking into consideration both long and short haul flights. The index also takes into account the percentage of diverted and cancelled flights on top of delayed flights giving a more holistic representation.

What is the seasonal effect on flight performance?

num_flights <- flights_cleaned %>% mutate(month=month(date)) %>% group_by(month) %>% summarise(num_flights=n())

delay_types <- flights_cleaned %>% select(AIR_SYSTEM_DELAY,SECURITY_DELAY,AIRLINE_DELAY,LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY,WEATHER_DELAY,date)
delay_types <- delay_types[complete.cases(delay_types),]
delay_types <- delay_types %>% mutate(month=month(date)) %>% 
  group_by(month) %>% 
  summarise(AIR_SYSTEM_DELAYS=sum(AIR_SYSTEM_DELAY!=0),
            SECURITY_DELAYS=sum(SECURITY_DELAY!=0),
            AIRLINE_DELAYS=sum(AIRLINE_DELAY!=0),
            LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAYS=sum(LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY!=0),
            WEATHER_DELAYS=sum(WEATHER_DELAY!=0)) %>% 
  merge(num_flights,by="month") %>% 
  mutate(AIR_SYSTEM_DELAYS_PERC=(AIR_SYSTEM_DELAYS/num_flights)*100,
         SECURITY_DELAYS_PERC=(SECURITY_DELAYS/num_flights)*100,
         AIRLINE_DELAYS_PERC=(AIRLINE_DELAYS/num_flights)*100,
         LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAYS_PERC=(LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAYS/num_flights)*100,
         WEATHER_DELAYS_PERC=(WEATHER_DELAYS/num_flights)*100)

From the visualisation, we can see that the periods with the greatest effects on delays are Jun-Jul and Dec-Feb. These periods experience the highest percentage of delays.

Taxi In and Out across the year

taxi_plot <- flights_cleaned %>% .[complete.cases(flights_cleaned$TAXI_OUT),] %>% 
  .[complete.cases(.$TAXI_IN),] %>% 
  mutate(month=month(date)) %>% 
  group_by(month) %>% 
  summarise(avrg_taxi_in=mean(TAXI_IN),avrg_taxi_out=mean(TAXI_OUT))

Taxi In Plot

Cancelled Flights

  summarise(cancelled_flights=sum(CANCELLED)) %>% 
  ggplot() + geom_line(aes(x=month,y=cancelled_flights)) + 
  geom_point(aes(x=month,y=cancelled_flights)) +
  labs(y="Cancelled Flights") +
  theme(axis.title.x=element_blank()) +

Combine Taxi In, Taxi Out and Cancelled Flights

grid.arrange(taxi_in,taxi_out,cancelled_flights,top="Seasonal Effect on Performance")

When comparing taxi durations, we find a similar trend, with Dec-Feb and Jun-Aug experiencing the highest average taxi in and out durations. The number of cancelled flights is also high in Jan, Feb, Jun and Dec. Notably, Feb has the highest number of cancellations by far.

Regions that experience the most weather delays

weather_delay <- flights_cleaned %>% filter(WEATHER_DELAY>0) %>% 
  select(ORIGIN_AIRPORT,WEATHER_DELAY) %>% 
  merge(x=.,y=airports,by.x="ORIGIN_AIRPORT",by.y="IATA_CODE") %>% 
  .[complete.cases(.),]

leaflet(weather_delay) %>% addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.DarkMatter) %>% 
  addWebGLHeatmap(lng=~LONGITUDE, lat=~LATITUDE, size = 200000)

This visualisation shows the regions which experience the most weather delays. From the map, we can see that weather delays occur most frequently in airports found near the coastline. However, there are more airports located near the coastlines and thus, the high density of weather delays in these regions could also be attributed to this.
